ground_truth: The different crop growing zones for Soybean include the North Eastern Hill zone, North Plain zone, Eastern zone, Central zone, and Southern zone. For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The North Plain zone has similar seed recommendations, but with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, and a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare. The Eastern zone follows the same recommendations as the North Eastern Hill zone. The Central zone also recommends the same seed varieties, with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 60 kg of P, 40 kg of K, and 20 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. Lastly, the Southern zone recommends the same seed varieties, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 80 kg of P, 20 kg of K, and 30 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing.

ground_truth: The weed management needs for soybean cultivation include dealing with broadleaf weeds and grasses such as Amaranthus, Echinochloa, and Phalaris. Various herbicides can be used, including Pendimethalin, Imazethapyr, Diclosulum, Sulfentrazone, Chlomozone, Flumioxazin, Metolachlor, Metribuzin, Pyroxasulfone, Chlorimuron ethyl, Bentazone, Imazethapyr, Quizalofop-ethyl, Fenoxaprop-p-ethyl, Fluazifop-p-butyl, Haloxyfop R Methyl, Propaquizafop, Fluthiacet methyl, Fluazifop-p-butyl + Fomesafen, Imazethapyr + Imazamox, Propaquizafop + Imazethapyer, Sodium Aceflourofen + ClodinafopPropargyl. The quantity of herbicide used varies depending on the specific herbicide, and they can be applied at different stages including pre-plant, pre-emergence, and post-emergence.

ground_truth: The disease treatment requirements for Soybean cultivation include treating for diseases like Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus. The symptoms of these diseases include sunken, dark brown lesions on the cotyledons of seedlings, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The control measures include using herbicides like Thiamethoxam and Imidachloprid in quantities of 10 mL/kg seed and 1.25 mL/kg seed respectively, at the seed treatment stage.

The symptoms of this disease are yellowing and wilting of leaves, and light gray discoloration in taproot and lower stem. The disease can be controlled by using the herbicide 'Carbendazim', applied at a quantity of '2 g per litre of water' at the time of sowing.

Temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C have a negative effect. The soil requirements include well-drained loamy to clayey loam soil, avoiding sandy and heavy black soils. The soil should have a medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity.

ground_truth: Soybean, a type of legume, is used for food and oil. It is grown in central India, specifically in regions like Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, and Rajasthan. Recommended seed varieties include JS 335, JS 95-60, and JS 93-05. The early sowing time is from 25th June to 5th July, and the late sowing time is from 25th July to 10th August. The seeding rate is 30 Kg per hectare. Fertilizer application requires 20 Kg of Nitrogen per hectare at the time of sowing. The temperature requirements for germination, flowering, and grain filling are 25-30°C, 20-25°C, and 20-25°C respectively. The crop does not tolerate temperatures above 35°C. The soil should be well drained loamy to clayey loam, rich in organic matter, and have moderate water holding capacity. Sandy soil should be avoided. The field should be ploughed thoroughly followed by planking and prepared to fine tilth stage with soil moisture at field capacity. Seeds should have more than 80% germination. Seed fungicide requirements include Thiram or Carbendazim at 2 g per Kg of seeds. Seed sowing spacing for the Kharif season is 30 cm x 10 cm at a depth of 3-4 cm using the dibbling method. Weed management includes controlling Phalaris minor with Glyphosate at 1.0 Kg per hectare post-emergence. Irrigation requirement is 500-600 mm at the flowering and pod development stage. Disease treatments for Charcoal rot include Carbendazim at 2 g per litre of water at the time of sowing. Pest treatments for Tobacco caterpillar include Quinalphos at 2 ml per litre of water at the larval stage. Harvesting should be done when 85-90% pods turn brown and hard. The harvested crop should be stored in a cool and dry place.

ground_truth: Soybean requires a temperature of 15-30°C for germination, 20-30°C for flowering, and 20-30°C for grain filling. It should not be exposed to temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C. The soil should be well-drained loamy to clayey loam, avoiding sandy and heavy black soils. The soil should have medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity. Deep ploughing is essential during summer, after harvesting the Rabi crop. The moisture content should be optimum for good germination. The seed sowing spacing should be 30-45 cm row to row and the depth should be 3 cm. The sowing time is after the arrival of monsoon. The crop requires irrigation at critical growth stages like seedling, flowering and pod filling. The crop is susceptible to various diseases and pests, and requires specific treatments as per occurrence.

ground_truth: The Soybean crop requires treatment for the disease RUST. The symptoms include chlorotic gray brown spots appearing on the leaves, increasing in size to form pustules. Eventually, leaves turn brown within a short time causing early defoliation and reduction in number of pods, seeds and seed weight. The presence of loose brown powder owing to rupture of pustules is a characteristic symptom. The disease can be controlled with the herbicide Hexaconazole 5% EC, applied at the initial stage of the disease. The crop also requires treatment for the pest YELLOW MOSAIC VIRUS (YMV). The pest can be controlled with the pesticides Thiamethoxam 30 FS and Imidacloprid 48 FS.

ground_truth: The seed sowing spacing requirements for soybean cultivation are 30-45 cm between rows, 5 cm within row. The seeds should be sown at a depth of 3-4 cm using the dibbling method. The recommended sowing time is June-July.

ground_truth: The disease treatment requirements for Soybean crops include treating diseases like Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus. The symptoms of these diseases include sunken, dark brown lesions on the cotyledons of seedlings, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The diseases can be controlled by using Thiamethoxam and Imidachloprid in quantities of 10 mL/kg seed and 1.25 mL/kg seed respectively, applied at the seed treatment stage.

ground_truth: The temperature requirements for growing soybeans are 15-30°C for germination, 20-30°C for flowering, and 20-30°C for grain filling. Temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C have a negative effect. The soil requirements include well-drained loamy to clayey loam soil, avoiding sandy and heavy black soils. The soil should have a medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity.

ground_truth: The different crop growing zones for Soybean include the North Eastern Hill zone, North Plain zone, Eastern zone, Central zone, and Southern zone. For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the North Plain zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 75 kg of P, 25 kg of K, and 37.5 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The Eastern zone has the same recommendations as the North Eastern Hill zone. For the Central zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 60 kg of P, 40 kg of K, and 20 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the Southern zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 80 kg of P, 20 kg of K, and 30 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing.

ground_truth: The disease treatment requirements for soybean crops include treating diseases like Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus. The symptoms of these diseases include sunken, dark brown lesions on the cotyledons of seedlings, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The control measures include using herbicides like Thiamethoxam and Imidachloprid in quantities of 10 mL/kg seed and 1.25 mL/kg seed respectively, at the seed treatment stage.

ground_truth: The different crop growing zones for Soybean include the North Eastern Hill zone, North Plain zone, Eastern zone, Central zone, and Southern zone. For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the North Plain zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 75 kg of P, 25 kg of K, and 37.5 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The Eastern zone has the same recommendations as the North Eastern Hill zone. For the Central zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 60 kg of P, 40 kg of K, and 20 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the Southern zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer application of 25 kg of N, 80 kg of P, 20 kg of K, and 30 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing.

ground_truth: Soybean is used for food, feed, and oil. It grows well in regions like Indore, Bhopal, and Gwalior in Madhya Pradesh. Recommended seed varieties include JS 335, JS 95-60, and JS 93-05. The sowing time is from June to July, with a seeding rate of 60-80 kg/ha. The soil should be loamy or sandy, well-drained, and rich in organic matter. The field should be ploughed 2-3 times and leveled, with well decomposed farmyard manure added. The seeds should have a germination rate of at least 80%. The fungicide Thiram is recommended at a quantity of 2-3 g/kg seed. The sowing spacing is 30-45 cm between rows and 5 cm within a row, at a depth of 3-4 cm. Weed management is necessary against broadleaf weeds and grasses. Irrigation is required at the flowering and pod filling stage, with a quantity of 500-600 mm. Diseases like Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus need to be treated with Thiamethoxam and Imidachloprid. Pests like White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, and Girdle Beetle need to be controlled with pesticides like Imidachloprid, Chlorpyrifos, Thichloprid, Profenophos, Betacyfluthrin + Imidacloprid, Thiamethoxam + Lambda Cyhalothrin, and Flubendiamide. Harvesting should be done when 85-90% pods have turned brown and lost their green color, with a seed moisture content of 10-12%. The harvested crop should be stored in a cool, dry place, preferably in hermetic storage bags for long-term storage.

The soil should have a medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity.

ground_truth: Soybean requires a temperature of 15-30°C for germination, 20-30°C for flowering, and 20-30°C for grain filling. It should not be exposed to temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C. The soil should be well-drained loamy to clayey loam, avoiding sandy and heavy black soils. The soil should have a medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity. Deep ploughing is essential during summer, after harvesting the Rabi crop. The moisture content should be optimum for good germination. The seed should have a minimum 70% germination. The fungicide Penflufen + Trifloxystrobine 38 FS should be used at a quantity of 1 ml/kg seed. The seeds should be sown after the arrival of monsoon, with a row to row spacing of 30-45 cm, at a depth of 3 cm. Weed management is necessary against various types of weeds including broadleaf weeds, grassy weeds, and sedges. Irrigation should be as per crop requirement, especially at critical growth stages like seedling, flowering and pod filling. Diseases and pests should be treated as per their occurrence. Harvesting should be done when the moisture percentage of soybean seed is around 14-16%. The storage place should be cool with aeration and insect free.

ground_truth: Soybean crop requires a temperature of 15-30°C for germination, 20-30°C for flowering, and 20-25°C for grain filling. It should not be exposed to temperatures above 35°C. The soil should be loamy or sandy, well-drained, and rich in organic matter. Clayey soil should be avoided. The field should be ploughed 2-3 times and leveled, with the addition of well decomposed farmyard manure. The seeds should have a germination rate of at least 80%. The fungicide Thiram should be used at a quantity of 2-3 g/kg seed. The sowing time is June-July, with a spacing of 30-45 cm between rows and 5 cm within the row, at a depth of 3-4 cm. The method used is Dibbling. Weed management is necessary against broadleaf weeds and grasses. The crop requires an irrigation of 500-600 mm at the flowering and pod filling stage. Diseases like Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus need to be treated. Pests like White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, Girdle Beetle need to be controlled. Harvesting should be done when 85-90% pods have turned brown and lost their green color. The moisture content of the seeds should be around 10-12%. The harvested crop should be stored in a cool, dry place.

ground_truth: For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended soybean seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94. The seeds should be sown between 15th June and 30th June, with a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare. The fertilizer application requirements are 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the North Plain zone, the recommended seed varieties are the same, but the sowing time is slightly later, between 20th June and 5th July. The seeding rate is higher, at 65 kg per hectare. The fertilizer application requirements are 25 kg of N, 75 kg of P, 25 kg of K, and 37.5 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The differences between the two zones are in the sowing time, seeding rate, and fertilizer application requirements.

ground_truth: The ideal soil for soybean is well-drained loamy to clayey loam with medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity. The ideal temperature for soybean germination is between 15-30°C. Harmful conditions for soybean include temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C, and sandy and heavy black soils.

ground_truth: For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended sowing time for Soybean is from 15th June to 30th June, with a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare. The fertilizer application requirements are 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare, applied at the time of sowing. For the Southern zone, the recommended sowing time is the same, but the seeding rate is higher at 65 kg per hectare. The fertilizer application requirements are also different, with 25 kg of N, 80 kg of P, 20 kg of K, and 30 kg of S per hectare, also applied at the time of sowing.

ground_truth: For pest management, the pests include White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, Girdle Beetle. The control measures include using pesticides like Imidachloprid, Chlorpyrifos, Thichloprid, Profenophos, Betacyfluthrin + Imidacloprid, Thiamethoxam + Lambda Cyhalothrin, Flubendiamide. For disease management, the diseases include Anthracnose, Yellow Mosaic Virus. The control measures include using herbicides like Thiamethoxam, Imidachloprid.

In Madhya Pradesh, the pest control strategy against Tobacco Caterpillar involves the use of pesticides including Imidachloprid, Chlorpyrifos, Thichloprid, Profenophos, Betacyfluthrin + Imidacloprid, Thiamethoxam + Lambda Cyhalothrin, Flubendiamide. ground_truth: For Soybean cultivation in Madhya Pradesh and Central India, the recommended seed varieties are JS 335, JS 95-60, and JS 93-05. The early sowing time is from June 1 to June 30, and the late sowing time is from July 1 to July 31. The seeding rate is 60-80 kg/ha. Nitrogen fertilizer is applied at sowing at a rate of 20 kg per hectare. The temperature requirements for germination, flowering, and grain filling are 15-30°C, 20-30°C, and 20-25°C respectively. The soil should be loamy or sandy, well-drained, and rich in organic matter. The field should be ploughed 2-3 times and leveled, with the addition of well decomposed farmyard manure. Seeds should have a germination rate of at least 80%. The fungicide Thiram is used at a rate of 2-3 g/kg seed. The sowing spacing is 30-45 cm between rows and 5 cm within the row, at a depth of 3-4 cm. Weed management involves dealing with broadleaf weeds and grasses, and the herbicides used vary depending on the weed. Irrigation is required at the flowering and pod filling stage, with a quantity of 500-600 mm. Diseases such as Anthracnose and Yellow Mosaic Virus need to be treated with Thiamethoxam and Imidachloprid. Pests like White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, and Girdle Beetle are controlled with various pesticides. Harvesting should occur when 85-90% of pods have turned brown and lost their green color, with a seed moisture content of 10-12%. The harvested crop should be stored in a cool, dry place, and hermetic storage bags are recommended for long-term storage.

ground_truth: Soybean cultivation requires different conditions across various Indian zones. In the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, and a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare. The fertilizer requirement is 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. Similar conditions apply to the Eastern zone. In the North Plain zone and Central zone, the sowing time is between 20th June and 5th July, with a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare. The fertilizer requirements vary slightly. In the Southern zone, the sowing time is between 15th June and 30th June, with a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and different fertilizer requirements. The temperature requirements for germination, flowering, and grain filling are 15-30°C, 20-30°C, and 20-30°C respectively. The soil should be well-drained loamy to clayey loam, with medium to high nutrient holding capacity. The land should be prepared with deep ploughing during summer, and the moisture content should be optimum for good germination. The seeds should be treated with Penflufen + Trifloxystrobine 38 FS fungicide, and sowing should be done after the arrival of monsoon, with 30-45 cm row to row spacing and at a depth of 3 cm. Weed management, irrigation schedule, disease treatments, pest treatments, harvesting guidelines, and storage guidelines are also specified.

ground_truth: For soybean cultivation, the temperature requirements are 15-30°C for germination, 20-30°C for flowering and grain filling. The crop is negatively affected by temperatures above 35°C and below 10°C. The soil requirements include well-drained loamy to clayey loam soil types, avoiding sandy and heavy black soils. The soil should have a medium water holding capacity and medium to high nutrient holding capacity.

ground_truth:
For Soybean cultivation in Central India and Madhya Pradesh, the following are needed: 

1. Seeds: Varieties like JS 335, JS 95-60, JS 93-05 are recommended. 
2. Sowing Time: Early sowing time is from 25-June to 5-July and late sowing time is from 25-July to 10-August. 
3. Seeding Rate: 30 Kg per hectare. 
4. Fertilizer: Nitrogen is required in the quantity of 20 Kg per hectare at the time of sowing. 
5. Temperature: For germination, the temperature should be 25-30°C, for flowering it should be 20-25°C, and for grain filling, it should be 20-25°C. Temperature above 35°C has a negative effect. 
6. Soil: Well drained loamy to clayey loam soil is required. Sandy soil should be avoided. The soil should have a moderate water holding capacity and should be rich in organic matter. 
7. Land Preparation: The field should be ploughed thoroughly followed by planking. The field should be prepared to a fine tilth stage with soil moisture at field capacity. 
8. Seed Germination: Seeds should have more than 80% germination. 
9. Fungicide: Thiram or Carbendazim is required in the quantity of 2 g per Kg of seeds. 
10. Seed Sowing Spacing: The value should be 30 cm x 10 cm with a depth of 3-4 cm. The method used should be Dibbling. 
11. Weed Management: The weed Phalaris minor should be managed with the herbicide Glyphosate in the quantity of 1.0 Kg per hectare at the post-emergence stage. 
12. Irrigation: 500-600 mm of water is required at the flowering and pod development stage. 
13. Disease Treatment: Charcoal rot disease should be treated with Carbendazim in the quantity of 2 g per litre of water at the time of sowing. 
14. Pest Treatment: Tobacco caterpillar pest should be treated with Quinalphos in the quantity of 2 ml per litre of water at the larval stage. 
15. Harvesting: Harvest when 85-90% pods turn brown and hard. 
16. Storage: Store in a cool and dry place.

The quantity for application varies from 2 ml per litre of water in Central India to 1.25 ml/kg seed, 16 kg/ha, 750 ml/ha, 1250 ml/ha, 350 ml/ha, 125 ml/ha, 150 ml/ha in Madhya Pradesh. The stage of application is the Larval stage in Central India and can vary from Seed treatment, Soil application, Spray in Madhya Pradesh.

ground_truth: For Soybeans, the pest management involves treating pests like White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, Girdle Beetle. The symptoms include drying of plants in linear patches, heavy yield losses, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The control measures include using pesticides like Imidachloprid, Chlorpyrifos, Thichloprid, Profenophos, Betacyfluthrin + Imidacloprid, Thiamethoxam + Lambda Cyhalothrin, Flubendiamide. The quantity varies from 1.25 ml/kg seed, 16 kg/ha, 750 ml/ha, 1250 ml/ha, 350 ml/ha, 125 ml/ha, 150 ml/ha and the stage of application is seed treatment, soil application, spray. The disease management involves treating diseases like Anthracnose, Yellow Mosaic Virus. The symptoms include sunken, dark brown lesions on the cotyledons of seedlings, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The control measures include using herbicides like Thiamethoxam, Imidachloprid with quantity 10 mL/kg seed, 1.25 mL/kg seed and the stage of application is seed treatment.

ground_truth: Soybean cultivation varies across different Indian regions. In the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with sowing time between 15th and 30th June, and a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare. The fertilizer requirement is 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare. In the North Plain zone, the same varieties are recommended, but the sowing time is between 20th June and 5th July, with a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare. The fertilizer requirement is 25 kg of N, 75 kg of P, 25 kg of K, and 37.5 kg of S per hectare. In Central India, the recommended varieties are JS 335, JS 95-60, and JS 93-05, with early sowing time between 25th June and 5th July, and late sowing time between 25th July and 10th August. The seeding rate is 30 kg per hectare, and the fertilizer requirement is 20 Kg of Nitrogen per hectare.

ground_truth: Soybean cultivation specifics vary by zone. For the North Eastern Hill zone, the recommended seed varieties are JS 20-116 and JS 20-94, with a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 55 kg per hectare, and fertilizer requirements of 25 kg of N, 100 kg of P, 50 kg of K, and 50 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For the North Plain zone, the same seed varieties are recommended, but the sowing time is between 20th June and 5th July, the seeding rate is 65 kg per hectare, and the fertilizer requirements are 25 kg of N, 75 kg of P, 25 kg of K, and 37.5 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The Eastern zone has the same recommendations as the North Eastern Hill zone. The Central zone recommends the same seed varieties, a sowing time between 20th June and 5th July, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer requirements of 25 kg of N, 60 kg of P, 40 kg of K, and 20 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. The Southern zone recommends the same seed varieties, a sowing time between 15th June and 30th June, a seeding rate of 65 kg per hectare, and fertilizer requirements of 25 kg of N, 80 kg of P, 20 kg of K, and 30 kg of S per hectare at the time of sowing. For Central India, the recommended seed varieties are JS 335, JS 95-60, and JS 93-05, with an early sowing time between 25-June and 5-July, a late sowing time between 25-July and 10-August, a seeding rate of 30 Kg per hectare, and fertilizer requirements of 20 Kg of Nitrogen per hectare at the time of sowing.

ground_truth: The pest control protocol for Soybean cultivation in Madhya Pradesh includes treating pests like White Grub, Gram Pod Borer, Tobacco Caterpillar, Green Semilooper, Girdle Beetle. The symptoms of these pests include drying of plants in linear patches, heavy yield losses, irregular reddish to dark brown areas on infected parts, yellowing of leaves with brown spot, defoliation of leaves under prolonged period of high humidity, leaves remain green while only pods turn yellow to brown. The control measures include using pesticides like Imidachloprid, Chlorpyrifos, Thichloprid, Profenophos, Betacyfluthrin + Imidacloprid, Thiamethoxam + Lambda Cyhalothrin, Flubendiamide. The quantity varies from 1.25 ml/kg seed, 16 kg/ha, 750 ml/ha, 1250 ml/ha, 350 ml/ha, 125 ml/ha, 150 ml/ha depending on the pesticide. The stage of application includes Seed treatment, Soil application, Spray.
